ITU Graphics Programming

Exercise 09 - Post processing

Learning objectives

Whiles practicing some post processing effects, we will learn:

  • The visual difference it makes to handle a HDR scene.
  • How to adjust the final color of the image in different ways.
  • How to efficiently implement a gaussian filter.

Remember that you can find hints in comments in the code, tagged with the label "(todo)" followed by the number of the exercise.

Exercise 09.0 - Quick overview of the code (live)

The teacher will quickly go through the different parts of the code, paying special attention to the renderer passes.

Exercise 09.1 - HDR tone-mapping

HDR allows the framebuffer to store values not clamped between 0 and 1. This is useful for example to handle scenes with very dark and very bright areas.

We will change the renderer to support HDR and will apply tone-mapping at the end to map to the range (0, 1). For the tone-mapping we will use a fixed exposure that we can modify from the UI.

In this application, the renderer is using deferred rendering. The deferred render pass, however, is not rendered to the window framebuffer. Instead, it is rendered to another framebuffer, m_sceneFramebuffer, and the copied to the window framebuffer in an additional pass.

This was done as a preparation for this exercise, and it is the first thing we will change:

  1. Locate the copy fragment shader file, in the "shaders/postfx" folder.
  2. Duplicate it and rename the new file to "compose.frag". This will be the shader that we will use for the final pass, including the tone-mapping.
  3. In C++, in the function InitializeRenderer(), modify the last pass to use the new compose shader. To be able to change the properties, assign the new material to m_composeMaterial, instead of using a local variable.
  4. Back to "compose.frag" shader, add a new uniform, of type float, named "Exposure". It is important to use the exact name, as it is connected to the GUI value.
  5. Use the new uniform to implement the tone mapping, using the formula explained during the lecture. For the exponential function, you can use the built-in function exp.

Run the program and play with the exposure value in the GUI. Notice how everything darkens when using low exponent values, even if you modify the light intensity to very high values.

This is because the scene framebuffer is not HDR, it can only store values between 0 and 1.

  1. In C++, find the code where we initialize the framebuffers, and identify the texture we are using for the color attachment.
  2. Change the internal format to a different one that can hold floating point values (F suffix). 16 bit should be enough for the exercise.
  3. Run the application again, and set the exposure value to the minimum. Do you notice any changes? (Pay attention to the lights on the wall).
  4. Still with the low exposure, use the GUI to modify the light intensity to a very high value and observe how now you can see more details.

Exercise 09.2 - Color grading

Video games usually need to apply post-processing after rendering the scene, to achieve a specific artistic look. We won't implement any advanced color grading filters, just some basic controls to understand how the image gets processed.

The filters we are going to implement will allow you to: adjust contrast, shift hue, adjust saturation and tint the image with a color.

We don't need new passes, all the filters will be implemented in compose fragment shader.

We will need 4 properties to control the effects:

  • Contrast (float): Range [0.5, 1.5]. Default value = 1. Adjusts the contrast of the image.
  • Hue Shift (float): Range [-0.5, 0.5]. Default value = 0. Rotates the hue of the image.
  • Saturation (float): Range [0.0, 2.0]. Default value = 1. Modifies the saturation of the colors in the image.
  • Color filter (vec3): Default value = White(1). Color that will multiply the entire image.

For each one of this properties, you need to:

  1. Add a member variable to the class, to store the value that will be used by the GUI.
  2. Add a new uniform to compose.frag.
  3. Implement the GUI, following the same pattern we used for exposure. For floats you can use ImGui::SliderFloat, and for color ImGui::ColorEdit3.
  4. Set the corresponding uniform value when the GUI has been modified (when the GUI controller returns true).

Finally, for the actual implementation of the effects, we have to modify the color in "compose.frag" AFTER the exposure has been applied:

Contrast: Substract 50% gray color (0.5) from the current color value, to center the values around 0. Multiply the result by the contrast uniform and add the same gray again. Clamp the result between 0 and 1.

Hue shift: Using the helper functions in utils.glsl (already included), convert the color to HSV format. Modify the hue (X component) by adding the hue shift uniform and take only the fractional part (built-in function fract). Convert the color back to RGB.

Saturation: Using the helper functions, compute the color luminance and substract it (as a vec3) from the current color value. Multiply the result by the saturation uniform and add the luminance again. Clamp the result between 0 and 1.

Color filter: Just multiply the color by the color filter uniform.

Exercise 09.3 - Blur

Blur post-processing consists in averaging the pixel color with the neighbors. In this implementation we will use a gaussian distribution with a 9x9 kernel.

Gaussian filters are separable, which means we can do 2 passes with one-dimensional kernels (9x1 + 1x9) instead of 1 pass with two-dimensional kernel (9x9), for performance reasons.

By taking advantage of linear filtering, we can reduce the number of samples to 7, instead of 9, for each pass. One centered, and 2 at each side, sampling between 2 pixels, for a total of 4 pixels at each side, 9 in total.

This is already implemented in the fragment shader, "blur.frag". Take a look and try to understand how it works.

The blur passes will work in separate textures, instead of changing the scene framebuffer. For that, we need to create 2 new ones, one for each pass:

  1. In the header file, declare an array of two framebuffers, and another array of two 2D textures.
  2. Find the function where we are creating the framebuffers.
  3. Create the new textures, with the same size and format as m_sceneTexture.
  4. Create the new framebuffers and use the corresponding textures as color attachments. We don't need depth attachments for these framebuffers.

The next step would be adding the new passes, in InitializeRenderer(), between the deferred passes and the compose pass:

  1. Create one postFX material for horizontal blur, and another one for vertical blur, using the same shader, "blur.frag". The horizontal pass will use first of the new textures as input, and the vertical pass will use the second one. You can use local variables for these materials, because we won't change them from the GUI.
  2. The new materials need to set one property: vec2 Scale. We will use this property to select the direction. For horizontal, the scale is (1/width, 0). For vertical, it is (0, 1/height).
  3. Finally, add the new postFX renderpasses. The horizontal blur will render to the second framebuffer, and the vertical blur to the first framebuffer. This way, the output image ends in the same texture where it started, and we could apply the blur several times if needed.

As you probably noticed, the new passes are still not connected to the other passes:

  1. For the compose pass, use the first of the new textures as input, instead of m_sceneTexture.
  2. We can't do the same for the deferred pass, because it needs a depth attachment. Instead, create a new copy pass (like the one initially had) to copy m_sceneTexture to the first of the new textures.

If you run the application now, everything should be blurred. If it didn't work, review all the steps.

If you move the camera around, you will notice that there are some artifacts on the edges. To fix this, you can set the texture parameters WrapS and WrapT to GL_CLAMP_TO_EDGE.

Exercise 09.4 - Bloom

Now that we have implemented blur, we can use it to implement the final effect of the exercise: Bloom.

As seen in the lecture, we need to detect those areas that are too bright, blur them, and add them to the scene.

To implement this effect we need to replace the copy pass we just added with a new pass, using a new shader:

  1. Duplicate "copy.frag" again and rename the new file to "bloom.frag".
  2. Create a new member variable for the bloom material.
  3. In InitializeRenderer(), create the bloom material, using m_sceneTexture as the source texture.
  4. Delete the copy pass we added in the previous exercise.
  5. Instead, add a new post FX pass with the bloom material, drawing to the first framebuffer of the blur pass.

The new shader will have 2 uniforms: vec2 Range and float Intensity:

  1. Declare the uniforms in the shader file.
  2. Declare member variables to control the uniforms from the GUI.
  3. Set the default value for the new variables, and use it to set the uniform value in the new material. You can use a default Range of (1, 2) and default Intensity of 1.
  4. Add the GUI for the new uniforms.

The shader implementation is simple:

  1. Read the color from the SourceTexture.
  2. Get the luminance of the color.
  3. Remap the luminance value to the range uniform: 0 if is less or equal than Range.x, 1 if it is greater or equal than Range.y, and linear values in between.
  4. Write the color value, multiplied by the remapped value and the Intensity uniform.

When you run the program, you can observe that we only see blurry parts of the image. Those parts are the ones that will bloom, you should play now with the new settings and observe how they affect the result.

Ideally the glow should extend further, but we are using a very small blur kernel. You can do additional blur passes to get better results.

To finalize the exercise, we need to combine the blooming image with the original scene:

  1. Add a new uniform BloomTexture in "compose.frag".
  2. In that shader, read from the new texture and add it to the color BEFORE applying the exposure.
  3. In C++, set the value of the new uniform to the first blurred texture.
  4. Set m_sceneTexture as the source texture for the compose pass.
  5. Run the program and play with the settings, to see the results.

Congratulations! We now have a PBR renderer with some post-processing effects.

Exercise 09.X - Get creative (optional)

  • Try dividing the colors in discrete steps, as we did during the cel-shading exercise.
  • Use the depth buffer to detect edges, comparing the depth to the neighbor pixels.
  • Implement your own passes, playing with different effects. You can get inspiration in ShaderToy (see references).
